---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Family Tree"
  description="Genealogical family tree of Herman (Zvi) Freiman — the Freiman and Rosen families of Boryslaw."
>
  <article class="prose">
    <h1>Family Tree</h1>
    <p>The following family structure has been established from available documentation and family oral history.</p>

    <h2>Family Structure</h2>
    <figure class="tree-figure">
      <img
        src="/photos/Freiman_family_tree.drawio.png"
        alt="Freiman family tree diagram — Herman Zvi Freiman, his parents Feibel and Shifra Rosen, first wife Brunya (one child, both killed in Holocaust), and second wife Ester with their five children: Shraga (Feivel), Eliyahu, Moshe, Bracha, and Josef"
      />
    </figure>

    <h2>First Marriage</h2>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Information</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Wife</td><td>Brunya</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Child</td><td>One child (name unknown)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Fate</td><td>Both killed during the Holocaust — Aktionen and deportations, Boryslaw 1941–1944</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Second Marriage</h2>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Information</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Wife</td><td>Ester FREIMAN (née unknown), b. April 15, 1920</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Married</td><td>1945, Poland</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Children</td><td>Shraga (Feivel), Eliyahu, Moshe, Bracha, Josef</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Known Name Variants</h2>
    <p>The family name appears in multiple transliterations across documents written in Polish, German, and Yiddish:</p>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Variant</th><th>Language / Context</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>FREIMAN</td><td>German and ITS documents</td></tr>
        <tr><td>FRAJMAN</td><td>Polish registry</td></tr>
        <tr><td>FREIMANN</td><td>Some ITS cards (double-n)</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>Herman's father's name (פייבל) similarly appears as Feibel, Faivel, Faifel, and Fajwel — all the same Yiddish name rendered phonetically in different languages.</p>

    <h2>Gaps &amp; Open Questions</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>First wife Brunya:</strong> Surname unknown. No documentary record found — known from family oral history.</li>
      <li><strong>Child of first marriage:</strong> Name unknown. Killed in the Holocaust together with Brunya.</li>
      <li><strong>Children of second marriage:</strong> Five children — Shraga (Feivel), Eliyahu, Moshe, Bracha (Brunya), Josef.</li>
      <li><strong>Siblings of Herman:</strong> Unknown. No documentation found for brothers or sisters.</li>
      <li><strong>Extended Rosen family (mother's side):</strong> Not documented in available sources.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>See <a href="/research/">Research Notes</a> for suggested archives that may hold additional genealogical information.</p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .tree-figure {
    margin: 1.25rem 0 2rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 3px;
    overflow: hidden;
    background: var(--color-parchment);
  }
  .tree-figure img {
    width: 100%;
    display: block;
  }
</style>
